I"<p>Trends are <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/boltzmann-distribution-links-macrostates-with-microstate-probabilities">macro</a> <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/neural-dynamicity-has-evolutionary-advantages">dynamics</a> of a system. They can be observed at a <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/glom-enables-hierarchical-representations-in-continuous-spaces">coarse level</a>. Seasonality is a <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/memeplexes-resemble-grativational-attractors">cyclic</a> <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/dynamical-systems-have-a-certain-anatomy">fluctuation</a> in such a system. By subtracting a polynomial approximation of the <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/dynamical-systems-have-a-certain-anatomy">emitted outputs</a>, one can observe the <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/dataset-size-influences-impact-of-noise">signal beyond the trend</a>. Similarly, deseasonalizing can be performed by subtracting values from season-length time points before.</p>
